      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0564P0-05439'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0564P0_19950607_GCR_225' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        The noble Earl said: This is a minor amendment. As currently drafted the provision repeats the <a href="/acts/social-work-scotland-act-1968">Social Work (Scotland) Act 1968</a> that when an appeal is made to the sheriff against the decision of a children's hearing, the sheriff shall hear the reasons for the appeal. On further consideration this wording is not necessary and indeed could even be taken as a restriction on the sheriff's power to hear an appeal. The amendment ensures a provision that the sheriff shall simply hear the appeal. I urge noble Lords to accept this amendment. I beg to move.
      </p>
      
